    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix incorrect transpose offsets in FFT functions causing memory corruption\n\n### Summary\nThe NEON-optimized FFT implementation in OAI contains incorrect offset values in several transpose operations, leading to memory corruption and incorrect FFT results. The issue affects 512-point, 2048-point, and 8192-point FFT functions.\n\nThe root cause is that the `transpose4_ooff` function calls use incorrect offset parameters. For an N-point FFT processed 8 elements at a time, the offset should be N/8, but several functions were using N/4 or other incorrect values.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/TOOLS/oai_dfts_neon.c`: \n  - Fixed dft512 function - changed transpose offset from 128 to 64\n  - Fixed idft512 function - changed transpose offset from 128 to 64  \n  - Fixed dft2048 function - changed transpose offset from 512 to 256\n  - Fixed idft2048 function - changed transpose offset from 512 to 256\n  - Fixed dft8192 function - changed transpose offset from 2048 to 1024\n  - Fixed idft8192 function - changed transpose offset from 2048 to 1024\n\n### Reproduction\nUnder heavy PHY processing load, users may observe:\n- Segmentation faults in PHY processing threads\n- Incorrect channel estimation and equalization results\n- PDSCH/PUSCH decoding failures with high BLER\n- Memory sanitizer errors indicating out-of-bounds accesses in FFT processing\n\nThe issue is most likely to manifest when processing large bandwidth configurations (100MHz+) where 2048-point and 8192-point FFTs are used frequently.\n"
}